<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1436,325,753]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,656,681]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
Records collected in this study show that this species inhabits deeper waters than the previously reported 
<quantity box="[252,309,693,717]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" unit="m" value="14.0">14 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Filander" box="[324,621,692,717]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" refString="Filander, Z. &amp; Griffiths, C. L. (2014) Additions to and revision of the South African echinoid fauna (Echinodermata: Echinoidea). African Natural History, 10, 47 - 56." type="journal article" year="2014">Filander &amp; Griffiths 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Clark &amp; Courtman-Stock" authorityYear="1976" box="[866,1176,692,717]" class="Echinoidea" family="Brissidae" genus="Brissopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="lyrifera" subSpecies="capensis">
<emphasis box="[866,1176,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Brissopsis lyrifera capensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by anterior part of test distinctively raised; by anterior petals being directed downwards and by white color.
</paragraph>
